 Parts of Metal Halide lamps. 
Fig.2 shows the inner parts and its various function of a 
metal halide lamp. The inner tube contains the electrodes 
and various metal halides, along with mercury and inert 
gases that make up the mix. The typical halides used are 
some combination of Sodium, Thallium, and Scandium 
and Dysprosium lodides. These iodides control the lamp''s 
spectral power distribution and provide color balance by 
combining the spectra of the various iocides used. 
Light is generated by creating an arc between the two 
electrodes located inside the inner arc tube. The inner arc 
tube is typically made of quartz, and this is a very harsh 
environment, with high temperatures approaching 1000°C 
and pressure of 3 or 4 atmospheres. 
